Recorded with a Song Meter Micro and isolated with the help of Kaleidoscope Software.

I realise it's not the best recording, because of the background noise.

However, it is a proud one for me and Iracambi, as it is the first recording of which the bird was identified. We are 95% certain of it being the Little Tinamou, as the frequency and length of the call are exactly the same as reference sounds on Xeno Canto and Ebird.

Please let us know if you think differently!

rmk: This remote recording features a vocal encounter between two Wrens. A full burst of Wren song lasts between four and five seconds, depending on how many 'segments' the bird includes.  On average, there are five segments, roughly one second for each, but one of these stands out as a trill. The notes in the trill are condensed and make a purring sound.  The trill is usually within the the song. It is never at the start but can be relegated to the end.  The two rivals in the clip are easy to distinguish in two ways. First, singer A is close to the microphone and his voice is therefore louder. Second, only A regularly uses a trill. Singer B does not use a trill - except once, when it is the final element in the song.  You can hear A at 0:01, 0:10 (trill at 0:13), 0:22 (trill at 0:25), 0:30 (trill at 0:33), 0:39 (no trill), 0:48 (trill at 0:51), 1:00 (trill at 1:03), 1:13 (trill at 1:16). B sings at 0:03 (trills at very end of this burst, at 0:08), 0:16, 0:34, 0:44 (brief start, then stops), 0:56 and 1:09. A CHIFFCHAFF can be heard in the background at 1:09  and a BLACKCAP sings briefly at 1:17.

rmk: Natural vocalizations from an adult male perched about 4m up in lower midstory of secondary forest along Discovery Trail of lodge with at least three others audible in background. First three series of multi-note songs followed by single-note louder songs and then another multinote. Bird maintained mouth open for the multi-note delivery, but proceeded to preen and move about on perch between louder single-note songs, when its mouth opened far wider, and it often moved its head forward as it vocalized. Pretty awesome to observe!
